<h2 id="moving-onto-jekyll">Moving onto Jekyll</h2>
<p>So Jekyll is where I noticed the some minor changes to the way we install Jekyll over previous versions. So fire up iTerm2 and enter the following command</p>
<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>gem install jekyll bundler
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Once this has done its thing let‚Äôs make sure Jekyll installed by typing</p>
<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>jekyll -v
</code></pre></div></div>

<h2 id="working-with-jekyll">Working with Jekyll</h2>
<p>So now you have Jekyll installed we can move on to the fun stuff, creating and running your first Jekyll site.
So let‚Äôs take our first step‚Äôs to create a new site, for this we need to change directory. I have a source directory which resides inside my documents directory, so let‚Äôs go to that within iTerm2.
Switch over to iTerm2 and type the following command, and this will change us in our source directory. Make sure we have this created first!</p>
<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>cd source
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>We now want to create our first site! In iTerm2 enter</p>
<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>jekyll new my-site
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Jekyll then creates a folder structure which contains the files needed for our new site. Once this has completed, we‚Äôll need to switch to our newly created site directory.</p>

<p>Switch back into iTerm2 enter</p>
<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>cd my-site
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>You should now be in your newly created site directory, and you will be pleased to know we‚Äôre coming to the end of this article!</p>

<p>So there‚Äôs one more command that needs to be run, and this is where the magic happens! Back into terminal we go and enter <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">jekyll s</code> you could also enter <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">jekyll serve</code>. The command simply starts up the Jekyll server locally.</p>

<p>And we‚Äôre done! So now in the background Jekyll is humming away watching our site files, so as you edit your sites files the site will update and rebuild. There are some things you‚Äôll need to look out for; occasionally things won‚Äôt update this maybe because you have updated your configuration file. If this does happen, simply hit CTRL + C inside terminal to cancel/stop Jekyll. And then restart the site again by using the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">jekyll s</code> command.</p>

<p>And that‚Äôs about it for now. I will be covering more on Jekyll in future articles, thanks for taking the time to read this.</p>

